         <Mapping_Notes>
            <Usage>Allowed</Usage>
            <Rationale>This is a well-known Composite of multiple weaknesses that must all occur simultaneously, although it is attack-oriented in nature.</Rationale>
            <Comments>While attack-oriented composites are supported in CWE, they have not been a focus of research. There is a chance that future research or CWE scope clarifications will change or deprecate them. Perform root-cause analysis to determine which weaknesses allow symlink following to occur, and map to those weaknesses. For example, predictable file names might be intended functionality, but creation in a directory with insecure permissions might not.</Comments>
            <Reasons>
               <Reason Type="Other" />
            </Reasons>
         </Mapping_Notes>
         <Notes>
            <Note Type="Research Gap">
               <xhtml:p>Symlink vulnerabilities are regularly found in C and shell programs, but all programming languages can have this problem. Even shell programs are probably under-reported.</xhtml:p>
               <xhtml:p>"Second-order symlink vulnerabilities" may exist in programs that invoke other programs that follow symlinks. They are rarely reported but are likely to be fairly common when process invocation is used [REF-493].</xhtml:p>
            </Note>
         </Notes>
